Believe the hype baby! Best Italian hoagie with a side of oil vinaigrette. French onion dip is dreamy. Homemade chips are awesome. Any ice cream sandwich with chocolate icecream is stellar! I was going to give 5 stars already based on the service and the amazing food. However, I noticed the owner ensuring proper mask wearing which I believe merits special distinction, especially given recent outbreaks. I noticed a couple walk into the restaurant with the man’s nose uncovered. The owner attempted to respectfully ask him to pull up his mask to cover up his nose. His girlfriend immediately said “F this”, and walked out the door. Me and the rest of the customers, relieved this restaurant was ensuring proper Covid prevention, cheered their departure . The girlfriend returned and in a threatening tone started shouting at the owner with her mask lowered, the well witted owner and employees then proceeded to efficiently remove the gaudy half maskers. 10 out of 5 stars. This was my first visit and I definitely will keep supporting businesses like this who still fulfill their public safety responsibilities. Owner and employees are epic!

The 4 stars is because it was my first time. I’ll be back, and often, so I’m betting it’ll quickly get the 5th star.  Now back to dreaming about that cookie.

i ate here because the ratings were pretty good. the lady at the register was nice but the food was absolutely disgusting. the bread was soggy. the steak they put in the sandwich had soo much fat on it. they have halloween decorations up. my brother pointed out the fact that 2 roaches were stuck in the fake spider webs they have up. unacceptable.

I lived in Philly for 8 years, and Arlene runs an absolutely perfect Philly-Jewish hoagie shop. You've got a cheesesteak that stands up to the best in Philly (John's Roast Pork, imo), as well as fantastic Jewish deli hoagies, a great Philly Italian hoagie, and a slew of other amazing options. Sure it's pricier than most "sandwiches," but this is a gem that's well worth it! You can't get authentic Philly hoagies like this in most cities, esp not ones this expertly crafted. I honestly couldn't live here without it! Thank you Arlene, you are a DC legend!!!!

UPDATE: finally trying the Breakfast options, as Bubs and Pops introduced morning breakfast hours  M-F. Classic breakfast hoagie (2 eggs, a meat typically bacon, cheese, leafy greens and tomato, on a roll) and Roasted Potatoes. Tastes were on point and quality, just like their normal sandwiches. They offer the 'Breakfast for Lunch' Sandwich all day.  Also tried their Oatmeal Walnut Chocolate Chip Ice Cream Sandwich. A good amount of vanilla ice cream sandwiched between 2 large cookies. Nicely wrapped in plastic for to-go options.  _____________  My favorite in DC proper. Philly native and appreciate the quality and rich flavors presented in each of their sammies and other items sold (owned by ex-Philly residents, like myself). And Chef Jonathan Taub has nice formal restaurant credentials, and is now supporting the family business.  Beer and a mixed soft drinks (and water, ask for a cup) complement well. (At the time of this writing) Prices typically range $10ish for large 1/2 sandwich and $18ish for a whole, for breakfast sandwich is around $5. Space is underground a few steps and not fancy at all (but clean). Loyalty punchcard offered too. Give this place a try, methinks you'll really enjoy it. Excellent cold and hot sandwiches with optional condiments (sweet and hot peppers, a 'spicy hoagie spread', horseradish, etc), very good bread and higher-end ingredient quality.  ----- (Update): they serve mostly the breakfast to lunch crowd. Currently M-F 8 to 4pm, and Sat 11am to 4pm.  They do occasionally run a unique Saturday night price fixed dinner, branded "Supper at Bubs". Multi course, prix fixe menu with wine, liquor and additional beverage pairings. Checkout their website to learn more, and to see when they may be running their next event.

Bub and Pop's was a really nice experience.  The team was very friendly and obviously enjoy  the restaurant. We had a modest group and got the larger central table - for a lengthy group discussion.  Never too noisy, no hurrying us out. Bub and Pop's is a neighborhood Italian deli pulling from a Philadelphia heritage, and it's worth a visit. Here's why:  1) Food: Despite the quirky atmosphere, the food is what stands out first. They make a variety of items, but their sandwiches are what they are known for. The Italian hoagie and beef steak are top sellers and come in full and half portions. The half was enough for me to feel content!  2) Atmosphere: With quirky knick knacks on the walls and photos of their most loyal fans, this place is loveable. It feels like home. They also have a photo of Guy Fieri since he highlighted them on his show, but the photos of the customers are centerfold. They care that much about their fans over celebrities.  3) Service: The owners are so kind and will make you feel like you've known them for years even if it's the first visit.  If you are in Dupont Circle, stop by this place. It's a DC classic and one of the most loved places in the city.

DC, I’ve failed you...at the very least I’ve severely disappointed you.  Me, the lover of Sando Shops across the country...me, the self-proclaimed SandoKing, had failed, in my 13 years of living here, to make my way to Bub and Pop’s.  This place is what a Sando Shop is supposed to be!  Had a Tuna Melt (pictured) and also got an Italian to-go.  Both were equally delicious in their own right, both had me slightly angered that this wasn’t my 50th time having them after being here for most of my adult life.  Bub and Pop’s is an institution in DC, a must visit, a place where you’ll always feel welcome, and, of course, always have an amazing Sando.  They do it right!

Bub and Pop's is my absolute favorite sandwich place in DC. They have monstrous hoagies absolutely piled high with fillings. The Rich Boy is by far my favorite; fresh crispy fried shrimp, arugula, insanely flavorful sweet peppers, mayo, and pickles. Ahh to die for! Ate at this place with the family while on a trip to DC. Went here looking for someplace local with good sandwiches for lunch and we were not disappointed! I own a restaurant and I love that the owner was at the register and her son is the chef! We ordered two cheesesteaks that were both very good. My son ordered the Bolognese which was obviously homemade red sauce with Italian sausage and homemade meatballs, very very good. I ordered a chicken Parmesan and it was excellent! Same homemade red sauce and a big piece of chicken. Bread was very good, being from Louisiana we always have French Bread and this was more sub/hoagie style and we loved it. Servings are very large and the place is very warm and welcoming. Not a big place, but we went at an off peak time and it was only about 1/4 full. Food came out very quickly and they had very cold beer! I would definitely recommend this place to anyone who loves good sandwiches, they have good options and if I ever make it back I will definitely be trying the Hebrew Hammer, it sounded excellent as well!

I stopped in at Bub and Pop’s towards the end of the lunch rush on a weekday and the place was still quite busy. The dining room was cozy with lots of fun odds and ends on the walls. The cheese steak was the best I’d ever eaten. A generous portion of meat, melted provolone, and homemade thousand island dressing were held together by a divinely soft hoagie roll. I ended up requesting an extra container of the dressing because it was so good. I added on a chai cola to round out my meal, which was unique treat. Service was speedy despite the full dining room and the food was absolutely delicious. Bub and Pop’s is a local DC treasure that’s definitely worth a special trip into the city.
This place has two main things going for it. Tons of character and really damn good sandwiches. Though it won't be the healthiest lunch you have it will be the tastiest

For one of the most famous sub shops in DC, the sandwiches are filled to the brim with meat and vegetables yet will empty your wallet pretty quick.  I got the iconic italian hoagie, and overall the quality was okay. The only gripe I would have is that the store is only open 5 hours a day, and that the sandwiches are hugely overpriced. For a place that was my first visit when I moved to DC, I can say now that having visited other sub shops that Bub and Pop's only has a lasting appeal for tourists. ~$20 for a sandwich...that's a pretty crazy price to be paying for something that is not a full meal.
